title: For Sale/Trade:  1943 Mosin Nagant M1891/59 Carbine All Matching Numbers
postcontent:
***Final price drop!!! Putting this on Gunbroker next week if it doesn't sell locally before then
 Starting bid there will be $150 with no reserve. Save both of us time and effort and buy it from me FTF for $150 cash.***


Up for sale or trade I have a 1943 Mosin Nagant M91/59 Carbine. All serial numbers are original and matching. No forced matches. Bore is dark like most but fairly clean and has good rifling. Appears ready to fire. Stock is original and in decent shape for the age with a few imperfections as would be expected of any War Time rifle. Front barrel band is incorrect. Someone had used a rear band on it at some point but it does have the correct arsenal markings. The bands can be had for around $10. The receiver has also been drilled and tapped for a scope mount but there is no scope or mount with it at this time. This is a round receiver rifle with the Izhevsk arsenal markings. For those of you that are not familiar with these rifles, this is not one of the standard $100 1891/30 rifles that are flooding the market. This is a carbine model. From what I have found in my research, there are three versions of the Russian carbine models. The M38, M44, and the M91/59. The M38s and M91/59s are less common to find now. The M44s are selling on Gunbroker for around $250.  Also interested in trades. Would be interested in a good .22 rifle semi auto (10/22, Marlin model 60, Mossberg Tactical 22), SKS, AR15 Lower Receiver or other parts, or nice Pump Shotgun. Feel free to offer other trades. If I am not interested I will let you know in a polite manner. Thanks for looking and feel free to ask questions.

title: For Sale:  Hammerless 357 Revolver: RUGER LCR
postcontent:
Here are the Ruger LCR's specifications:

    Model number: 5401
    Caliber 357/ 38 Sp +P
    Capacity: 5
    Barrel material: 17-4 PH stainless steel
    Barrel length: 1.875 inches
    Grooves: 6
    Twist: 1-16 inches, right hand
    Frame finish: Matte black, synergistic hard coat
    Fire control housing: Long-strand, glass-fiber filled polymer
    Cylinder finish: New - Advanced Target Grey
    Sights: Integral, square notch rear; replaceable, pinned ramp front
    Sight radius: 3.75 inches
    Length: 6.5 inches
    Height: 4.5 inches
    Maximum width: 1.283 inches
    Weight: 17.1 ounces
    MSRP:$599



These are excerpts By Randy Wakeman from his 2009 review titled: "Ruger's LCR: The Best .38 Pocket Revolver Ever:
?available at:
http://www.chuckhawks.com/ruger_LCR_revolver.htm


(SELLER'S NOTE: The LCR is offered in 3 Calibers:  22LR, 38 Sp and +P, and 357 cal.)

Ruger's new for 2009 Lightweight Compact Revolver has been billed as the “Evolution of the Revolver.” It has proved to be at least that, if not more. Weighing in at roughly three quarters of a pound, it is hard not to notice how light this wheelgun is for a .38 Special +P revolver and how well it fits the hand. The barrel is only 1-7/8 in. long, the 5-shot revolver itself 1-1/4 inches wide. This is essentially in the J-frame genre of compact revolver, a bit lighter and less costly than the clunky S&W 642 series and the many variants of the platform, including the S&W Model 438 Bodyguard.


What quickly and dramatically sets the Ruger LCR apart from and ahead of the many old 5-shot, double action .38 Specials is the wondrous double-action trigger pull. While the trigger gauge shows it as about a nine pound trigger, Ruger has refined the trigger geometry and spring rates so it feels much lighter. The LCR has a smooth and consistent trigger pull that makes it relatively easy to cycle the cylinder and fire this revolver while maintaining a constant sight picture. As that is the whole idea with a personal defense pistol, Ruger can't be commended too highly for pulling this one off. It has an out-of-the box feel as if it had been tuned by the likes of Jack Weigand. The LCR is that smooth.

The primary ammo used was the Stars & Stripes Custom Ammo 125 grain Speer Gold Dot combat rounds. Shooting through the CED M2 chrono screens, the 5 foot velocity ranged from 767 – 796 fps, which is formidable, especially taking into consideration the diminutive 1-1/8 inch LCR barrel. After shooting fifty rounds of this ammo through the Ruger LCR, I can't call this revolver the ideal plinker by any means, but calling the recoil quite manageable is a fair assessment. It was surprisingly manageable considering the light weight of this handgun. For comparison, let me mention one of my least favorite type of handguns, the common .380 blowback semi-auto. Many of them are just nasty little palm-slappers, with crummy trigger pulls and an unfortunate propensity to stovepipe. Often you'll find them with merciless hard plastic crucifix type grips and slides that find new ways to slice the top of your hand, as well.
The above specs are from Ruger.com


SEE REVIEW OF THE RUGER  LCR AT:
 http://pocket-defense.com/2010/03/ruger-lcr-review/

title: For Sale/Trade:  NAZI RELIC PISTOL -THEODORE KOMMER .32ACP
postcontent:
Kommer Waffenfabrik GmbH, Zella Mehlis. 32ACP! 
 According to 'Pistols of the World' Theodor Kommer made Four models were eventualy produced, all based on Browning designs. The first three copied the Mod. 1906, the last was based on the 1910. 
... only some of those had the name Kommer on the grips (most just had "Th K" in an oval. ...all Kommer production ceased in 1940."
 produced by Theodor Kommer Waffenfabrik GmbH, Zella Mehlis. It is almost an exact copy of the Belgian, FN Browning Model 1910. 

the Kommer Model 4 is not a commonly encountered pistol,German police and civil guard were known to carry as well as some officers.
 production about 1936 and ceased in 1940 with only a small quantity made during this period. A very difficult pistol to locate for ones collection. Right slide is blank.  Left side is stamped: Waffen Fabrik Kommer Zella-Mehlis Kal 7.65 (Zella-Mehlis was also the home of the Walther factory) Only other markings on handgun is the serial # on left trigger guard: 15,xxx  Eagle over N proof (used after 4/1/1940 throughout WWII). Of interest there are sights both intact front and rear with grooving running down top of the slide.  A left rear safety.  The magazine has a rear knurled clasp to release. pistol is in fair shape with slight pitting and wear on the slide only!!! . the bore is very bright, with very clean internals with hardly any wear, I have fired 2 magazines without a hiccup. crisp clean action! the pistol comes with two original magazines no holster.. prime example of a wartime nazi pistol, not many produced,,rare!!!! clearing out some wartime and pre war relic pistols, 
last two of these i saw sold on guns america for 975 and one for 600 +shipping & transfer fees.........REDACTED call or text
